        <h3>A cycle governed by a biological clock</h3>
        <p>Human, like other living organisms, has a biological clock which is responsible for circadian rhythm i.e. biological functions that happen in a cyclic manner. Such biological-clock-controlled events are responsible for certain essential functions like sleep, which is common to both sexes, and certain gender-specific functions like the reproductive cycle in females.</p>
        <p>In the female, under the control of hormones, the reproductive organs — ovary &amp; uterus — exhibit certain features/functions in a cyclic manner, which are also influenced by factors like environment, stress, infections, and structural abnormalities. Being cyclical and changing constantly, it is often difficult to differentiate normal and abnormal functioning, especially when the pathology is subtle.</p>

        <h3>Conditions that can affect reproductive health</h3>
        <p>Conditions affecting the female reproductive tract/organs generally fall into three categories. Early diagnosis of these conditions greatly helps in achieving a better outcome and avoiding complications.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Endocrine related</strong> — e.g. menarche, menopause, PCO, PCOS</li>
          <li><strong>Structural abnormalities</strong> — e.g. fibroids, adenoma, polyps</li>
          <li><strong>Infectious causes</strong> — sexually and non-sexually transmitted, e.g. trichomoniasis, genital warts, syphilis, gonorrhea</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Simple signs before seeking medical advice</h3>
        <p>Diagnostic approaches towards these disorders typically involve expensive, complicated, and time-consuming tests — imaging studies, hormone analyses, biochemical and microbiological screening. However, at a first level, simple observations and easy-to-perform checks — pattern and quantity of menstrual bleeding, certain signs in the genitalia, the nature of vaginal discharge — can help establish the possibility of certain pathology. This simple approach can be very useful for a first-level read before deciding to seek professional medical advice.</p>

        <div class="content-note">
          This website describes simple, self-employable steps towards spotting potential complications in the female reproductive system. It is not a substitute for professional medical advice — it is intended for primary-level self-examination for those who are apprehensive.
        </div>
      </article>

